** Getting started
This new release was built by the Slurm experts at SchedMD. You can download this release in SchedMD’s GitHub repository.-- https://github.com/SchedMD/slurm-gcp

For more information, check out the included README. And if you need help getting started with Slurm check out the quick start guide -- https://slurm.schedmd.com/quickstart.html, 
 
 and for help with the Slurm features for GCP check out the Slurm Auto-Scaling Cluster -- https://codelabs.developers.google.com/codelabs/hpc-slurm-on-gcp/#0
  
  and Slurm Cluster Federation codelabs -- https://codelabs.developers.google.com/codelabs/hpc-slurm-federated-on-gcp/#0

If you have further questions, you can post on the Slurm on GCP Google discussion group -- https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/google-cloud-slurm-discuss

or contact SchedMD directly -- https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/google-cloud-slurm-discuss

answer:
https://github.com/SchedMD/slurm-gcp/blob/d2a4d8c822696f1cdebea2c682b1a551ba82071b/scripts/startup-script.py#L226 is where we pip install the python libs
**** Final solution


Solved by modifying startup-script.py to use the python2 version of pip ('/usr/bin/pip') and adding '--skip-broken' to yum install:

    while subprocess.call(['yum', 'install', '-y', '--skip-broken'] + packages):
        print "yum failed to install packages. Trying again in 5 seconds"
        time.sleep(5)

    while subprocess.call(['/usr/bin/pip', 'install', '--upgrade',
        'google-api-python-client']):
        print "failed to install google python api client. Trying again 5 seconds."
        time.sleep(5)

Voltage times and i_membrane_ are same and difference is less than 1e-10
** coreneuron/tests/jenkins/neuron_direct.py
from neuron import h, gui
import sys

h('''create soma''')
h.soma.L=5.6419
h.soma.diam=5.6419
h.soma.insert("hh")
ic = h.IClamp(h.soma(.5))
ic.delay = .5
ic.dur = 0.1
ic.amp = 0.3

h.cvode.use_fast_imem(1)
h.cvode.cache_efficient(1)

v = h.Vector()
v.record(h.soma(.5)._ref_v, sec = h.soma)
i_mem = h.Vector()
i_mem.record(h.soma(.5)._ref_i_membrane_, sec = h.soma)
tv = h.Vector()
tv.record(h._ref_t, sec=h.soma)
h.run()
vstd = v.cl()
tvstd = tv.cl()
i_memstd = i_mem.cl()

#h.CoreNeuronRun[0].run()
pc = h.ParallelContext()
h.stdinit()
pc.nrncore_run("-e %g"%h.tstop, 0)

if not bool(tv.eq(tvstd)):
    print("Voltage times are different")
    sys.exit(-1)
if v.cl().sub(vstd).abs().max() >= 1e-10:
    print(v.cl().sub(vstd).abs())
    print("Voltage difference greater than or equal to 1e-10")
    sys.exit(-1)
if i_mem.cl().sub(i_memstd).abs().max() >= 1e-10:
    print("i_mem difference greater than or equal to 1e-10")
    sys.exit(-1)

print("Voltage times and i_membrane_ are same and difference is less than 1e-10")
h.quit()

#!/bin/bash
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# nrnivmodl-core uses make to compile additonal mod files for coreneuron
# Copyright 2019 Blue Brain Project
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
set -e

APP_NAME=$(basename $0)
_PARENT="$(dirname $BASH_SOURCE)/.."
ROOTDIR=$(perl -e "use Cwd 'abs_path'; print abs_path('$_PARENT')")
MAKE_OPTIONS="NMODL_BINARY MECH_VERSION OUTPUT INCFLAGS LINKFLAGS MODS_PATH VERBOSE"
PARALLELISM=4

while getopts "n:v:o:i:l:p:hV" OPT; do
    case "$OPT" in
    n)
        params_NMODL_BINARY="$OPTARG";;
    v)
        params_MECH_VERSION="$OPTARG";;
    o)
        params_OUTPUT="$OPTARG";;
    i)
        params_INCFLAGS="$OPTARG";;
    l)
        params_LINKFLAGS="$OPTARG";;
    V)
        params_VERBOSE=1;;
    p)
        PARALLELISM="$OPTARG";;
    h)
        echo "$APP_NAME [options, ...] [mods_path]"
        echo "Options:"
        echo "  -n <binary>     NMODL code generation compiler path"
        echo "  -v <version>    Set libcorenrnmech version (default: 0.0)"
        echo "  -o <output_dir> Set the output dir (default: <arch>-core)"
        echo "  -i <incl_flags> Definitions passed to the compiler, typically '-I dir..'"
        echo "  -l <link_flags> Definitions passed to the linker, typically '-Lx -lylib..'"
        echo "  -V              Verbose: show commands executed by make"
        echo "  -p <n_procs>    Make parallelism. Default: 4"
        exit 0;;
    ?)
        exit 1;;
    esac
done

shift $(($OPTIND - 1))

if [ $# -gt 1 ]; then
    echo "Error: $APP_NAME expects at most one mod dir. See syntax: '$APP_NAME -h' "
    exit 1
fi

# If defined mods dir be in $1
# Note: due to bug #712 makefile wont handle mod dir with spaces, so we let it fail here
params_MODS_PATH=$1

make_params=("ROOT=${ROOTDIR}")

for param in $MAKE_OPTIONS; do
    var="params_${param}"
    [ "${!var+x}" ] && make_params+=("$param=${!var}")
done

# warn if no mod files provided
ls "${params_MODS_PATH:-.}"/*.mod || echo "Warning: No mods found!"
make -j$PARALLELISM -f "${ROOTDIR}/share/coreneuron/nrnivmodl_core_makefile" "${make_params[@]}"

# Create a little script to call make install (relinks w right RPATH)
# This should allow splitting the build of special-core into two phases:
# 1. build the binary from the libcoreneuron.so library and the compiled models
# 2. install into the final destination directory and relinking as necessary
# TODO: instead of outputting a script we could output an options file which would be read by
# this script when installing to ensure the same arguments are being used.
echo "#!/bin/bash
set -e
[ \$# -eq 1 ] || { echo 'Required install destination. Syntax: ' \$(basename \$0) '<directory>'; false; }
set -x
make -f '${ROOTDIR}/share/coreneuron/nrnivmodl_core_makefile' " $(printf "'%s' " "${make_params[@]}") "DESTDIR=\$1 install
" > nrnivmech_install.sh
chmod 755 nrnivmech_install.sh

echo "mods built successfully. Install script written to nrnivmech_install.sh"

[root@instance-1 mod]# cat cadad.mod
: $Id: cadad.mod,v 1.4 2002/11/08 15:42:37 billl Exp $
TITLE Fast mechanism for submembranal Ca++ concentration (cai)
:
: Takes into account:
:
:	- increase of cai due to calcium currents
:	- extrusion of calcium with a simple first order equation
:
: This mechanism is compatible with the calcium pump "cad" and has the 
: same name and parameters; however the parameters specific to the pump
: are dummy here.
:
: Parameters:
:
:	- depth: depth of the shell just beneath the membran (in um)
:	- cainf: equilibrium concentration of calcium (2e-4 mM)
:	- taur: time constant of calcium extrusion (must be fast)
:	- kt,kd: dummy parameters
:
: Written by Alain Destexhe, Salk Institute, 1995
:

INDEPENDENT {t FROM 0 TO 1 WITH 1 (ms)}

NEURON {
  SUFFIX cadad
  USEION ca READ ica, cai WRITE cai
  RANGE depth,kt,kd,cainf,taur
}

UNITS {
  (molar) = (1/liter)			: moles do not appear in units
  (mM)	= (millimolar)
  (um)	= (micron)
  (mA)	= (milliamp)
  (msM)	= (ms mM)
}

CONSTANT {
  FARADAY = 96489		(coul)		: moles do not appear in units
  :	FARADAY = 96.489	(k-coul)	: moles do not appear in units
}

PARAMETER {
  depth	= 1	(um)		: depth of shell
  taur	= 5	(ms)		: rate of calcium removal
  cainf	= 2.4e-4	(mM)
  kt	= 0	(mM/ms)		: dummy
  kd	= 0	(mM)		: dummy
}

STATE {
  cai		(mM) 
}

INITIAL {
  cai = cainf
}

ASSIGNED {
  ica		(mA/cm2)
  drive_channel	(mM/ms)
}
	
BREAKPOINT {
  SOLVE state METHOD cnexp
}

DERIVATIVE state { 
  drive_channel =  - (10000) * ica / (2 * FARADAY * depth)
  if (drive_channel <= 0.) { drive_channel = 0. }	: cannot pump inward
  cai' = drive_channel + (cainf-cai)/taur
}

: $Id: cadad.mod,v 1.4 2002/11/08 15:42:37 billl Exp $
TITLE Fast mechanism for submembranal Ca++ concentration (cai)
:
: Takes into account:
:
:	- increase of cai due to calcium currents
:	- extrusion of calcium with a simple first order equation
:
: This mechanism is compatible with the calcium pump "cad" and has the 
: same name and parameters; however the parameters specific to the pump
: are dummy here.
:
: Parameters:
:
:	- depth: depth of the shell just beneath the membran (in um)
:	- cainf: equilibrium concentration of calcium (2e-4 mM)
:	- taur: time constant of calcium extrusion (must be fast)
:	- kt,kd: dummy parameters
:
: Written by Alain Destexhe, Salk Institute, 1995
:

INDEPENDENT {t FROM 0 TO 1 WITH 1 (ms)}

NEURON {
  SUFFIX cadyn
  USEION ca READ ica, cai WRITE cai
  RANGE depth,kt,kd,cainf,taur
}

UNITS {
  (molar) = (1/liter)			: moles do not appear in units
  (mM)	= (millimolar)
  (um)	= (micron)
  (mA)	= (milliamp)
  (msM)	= (ms mM)
}

CONSTANT {
  FARADAY = 96489		(coul)		: moles do not appear in units
  :	FARADAY = 96.489	(k-coul)	: moles do not appear in units
}

PARAMETER {
  depth	= 1	(um)		: depth of shell
  taur	= 5	(ms)		: rate of calcium removal
  cainf	= 2.4e-4	(mM)
  kt	= 0	(mM/ms)		: dummy
  kd	= 0	(mM)		: dummy
}

STATE {
  cai		(mM) 
}

INITIAL {
  cai = cainf
}

ASSIGNED {
  ica		(mA/cm2)
  drive_channel	(mM/ms)
}
	
BREAKPOINT {
  SOLVE state METHOD cnexp
}

DERIVATIVE state { 
  drive_channel =  - (10000) * ica / (2 * FARADAY * depth)
  if (drive_channel <= 0.) { drive_channel = 0. }	: cannot pump inward
  cai' = drive_channel + (cainf-cai)/taur
}

TITLE Anomalous rectifier current for RD Traub, J Neurophysiol 89:909-921, 2003

COMMENT

	Implemented by Maciej Lazarewicz 2003 (mlazarew@seas.upenn.edu)

ENDCOMMENT

INDEPENDENT { t FROM 0 TO 1 WITH 1 (ms) }

UNITS { 
	(mV) = (millivolt) 
	(mA) = (milliamp) 
} 
NEURON { 
	SUFFIX cadad
	NONSPECIFIC_CURRENT i
	RANGE gbar, i
}
PARAMETER { 
	gbar = 0.0 	(mho/cm2)
	v		(mV) 
	erev = -35	(mV)  
} 
ASSIGNED { 
	i 		(mA/cm2) 
	minf 		(1)
	mtau 		(ms) 
} 
STATE {
	m
}
BREAKPOINT { 
	SOLVE states METHOD cnexp
	i = gbar * m * ( v - erev ) 
} 
INITIAL { 
	minf  = 1 / ( 1 + exp( ( v + 75 ) / 5.5 ) )
	mtau = 1 / ( exp( -14.6 - 0.086 * v ) + exp( -1.87 + 0.07 * v ) )
	m = minf
	: m = 0.25 : ??
} 
DERIVATIVE states { 
	minf  = 1 / ( 1 + exp( ( v + 75 ) / 5.5 ) )
	mtau = 1 / ( exp( -14.6 - 0.086 * v ) + exp( -1.87 + 0.07 * v ) )
	m' = ( minf - m ) / mtau 
}

: $Id: cadad.mod,v 1.4 2002/11/08 15:42:37 billl Exp $
TITLE Fast mechanism for submembranal Ca++ concentration (cai)
:
: Takes into account:
:
:	- increase of cai due to calcium currents
:	- extrusion of calcium with a simple first order equation
:
: This mechanism is compatible with the calcium pump "cad" and has the 
: same name and parameters; however the parameters specific to the pump
: are dummy here.
:
: Parameters:
:
:	- depth: depth of the shell just beneath the membran (in um)
:	- cainf: equilibrium concentration of calcium (2e-4 mM)
:	- taur: time constant of calcium extrusion (must be fast)
:	- kt,kd: dummy parameters
:
: Written by Alain Destexhe, Salk Institute, 1995
:

INDEPENDENT {t FROM 0 TO 1 WITH 1 (ms)}

NEURON {
  SUFFIX cadad
  USEION ca READ ica, cai WRITE cai
  RANGE depth,kt,kd,cainf,taur
}

UNITS {
  (molar) = (1/liter)			: moles do not appear in units
  (mM)	= (millimolar)
  (um)	= (micron)
  (mA)	= (milliamp)
  (msM)	= (ms mM)
}

CONSTANT {
  FARADAY = 96489		(coul)		: moles do not appear in units
  :	FARADAY = 96.489	(k-coul)	: moles do not appear in units
}

PARAMETER {
  depth	= 1	(um)		: depth of shell
  taur	= 5	(ms)		: rate of calcium removal
  cainf	= 2.4e-4	(mM)
  kt	= 0	(mM/ms)		: dummy
  kd	= 0	(mM)		: dummy
}

STATE {
  cai		(mM) 
}

INITIAL {
  cai = cainf
}

ASSIGNED {
  ica		(mA/cm2)
  drive_channel	(mM/ms)
}
	
BREAKPOINT {
  SOLVE state METHOD cnexp
}

DERIVATIVE state { 
  drive_channel =  - (10000) * ica / (2 * FARADAY * depth)
  if (drive_channel <= 0.) { drive_channel = 0. }	: cannot pump inward
  cai' = drive_channel + (cainf-cai)/taur
}

: $Id: cadad.mod,v 1.4 2002/11/08 15:42:37 billl Exp $
TITLE Fast mechanism for submembranal Ca++ concentration (cai)
:
: Takes into account:
:
:	- increase of cai due to calcium currents
:	- extrusion of calcium with a simple first order equation
:
: This mechanism is compatible with the calcium pump "cad" and has the 
: same name and parameters; however the parameters specific to the pump
: are dummy here.
:
: Parameters:
:
:	- depth: depth of the shell just beneath the membran (in um)
:	- cainf: equilibrium concentration of calcium (2e-4 mM)
:	- taur: time constant of calcium extrusion (must be fast)
:	- kt,kd: dummy parameters
:
: Written by Alain Destexhe, Salk Institute, 1995
:

INDEPENDENT {t FROM 0 TO 1 WITH 1 (ms)}

NEURON {
  SUFFIX cadad
  USEION ca READ ica, cai WRITE cai
  RANGE depth,kt,kd,cainf,taur
}

UNITS {
  (molar) = (1/liter)			: moles do not appear in units
  (mM)	= (millimolar)
  (um)	= (micron)
  (mA)	= (milliamp)
  (msM)	= (ms mM)
}

CONSTANT {
  FARADAY = 96489		(coul)		: moles do not appear in units
  :	FARADAY = 96.489	(k-coul)	: moles do not appear in units
}

PARAMETER {
  depth	= 1	(um)		: depth of shell
  taur	= 5	(ms)		: rate of calcium removal
  cainf	= 2.4e-4	(mM)
  kt	= 0	(mM/ms)		: dummy
  kd	= 0	(mM)		: dummy
}

STATE {
  cai		(mM) 
}

INITIAL {
  cai = cainf
}

ASSIGNED {
  ica		(mA/cm2)
  drive_channel	(mM/ms)
}
	
BREAKPOINT {
  SOLVE state METHOD cnexp
}

DERIVATIVE state { 
  drive_channel =  - (10000) * ica / (2 * FARADAY * depth)
  if (drive_channel <= 0.) { drive_channel = 0. }	: cannot pump inward
  cai' = drive_channel + (cainf-cai)/taur
}

TITLE Anomalous rectifier current for RD Traub, J Neurophysiol 89:909-921, 2003

COMMENT

	Implemented by Maciej Lazarewicz 2003 (mlazarew@seas.upenn.edu)

ENDCOMMENT

INDEPENDENT { t FROM 0 TO 1 WITH 1 (ms) }

UNITS { 
	(mV) = (millivolt) 
	(mA) = (milliamp) 
} 
NEURON { 
	SUFFIX cadad
	NONSPECIFIC_CURRENT i
	RANGE gbar, i
	RANGE depth,kt,kd,cainf,taur
}
PARAMETER { 
	gbar = 0.0 	(mho/cm2)
	v		(mV) 
	erev = -35	(mV) 
	  depth = 1     (um)            : depth of shell
  taur  = 5     (ms)            : rate of calcium removal
  cainf = 2.4e-4        (mM)
  kt    = 0     (mM/ms)         : dummy
  kd    = 0     (mM)            : dummy 
} 
ASSIGNED { 
	i 		(mA/cm2) 
	minf 		(1)
	mtau 		(ms) 
} 
STATE {
	m
}
BREAKPOINT { 
	SOLVE states METHOD cnexp
	i = gbar * m * ( v - erev ) 
} 
INITIAL { 
	minf  = 1 / ( 1 + exp( ( v + 75 ) / 5.5 ) )
	mtau = 1 / ( exp( -14.6 - 0.086 * v ) + exp( -1.87 + 0.07 * v ) )
	m = minf
	: m = 0.25 : ??
} 
DERIVATIVE states { 
	minf  = 1 / ( 1 + exp( ( v + 75 ) / 5.5 ) )
	mtau = 1 / ( exp( -14.6 - 0.086 * v ) + exp( -1.87 + 0.07 * v ) )
	m' = ( minf - m ) / mtau 
}

import argparse
import os
import pprint
import time
import uuid

project_id = 'ecas-2019'

# [START monitoring_read_timeseries_reduce]
client = monitoring_v3.MetricServiceClient()
project_name = client.project_path(project_id)
interval = monitoring_v3.types.TimeInterval()
now = time.time()
interval.end_time.seconds = int(now)
interval.end_time.nanos = int(
    (now - interval.end_time.seconds) * 10**9)
interval.start_time.seconds = int(now - (6*7*24*60*60))  # 6 weeks before
interval.start_time.nanos = interval.end_time.nanos
aggregation = monitoring_v3.types.Aggregation()
aggregation.alignment_period.seconds = 1200  # 20 minutes
aggregation.per_series_aligner = (
    monitoring_v3.enums.Aggregation.Aligner.ALIGN_MEAN)
aggregation.cross_series_reducer = (
    monitoring_v3.enums.Aggregation.Reducer.REDUCE_MEAN)
aggregation.group_by_fields.append('resource.zone')

results = client.list_time_series(
    project_name,
    'metric.type = "compute.googleapis.com/instance/cpu/utilization"',
    interval,
    monitoring_v3.enums.ListTimeSeriesRequest.TimeSeriesView.FULL,
    aggregation)
for result in results:
    print(result)

* 20Apr3 Setting up Placement groups

** README from GCP
# Slurm on Google Cloud Platform - Placement Group Beta Preview

The following describes compute instance provisioning support for slurm cluster compute nodes 
on GCP Placement Group Beta Preview.

First, review [Slurm on GCP code lab](https://codelabs.developers.google.com/codelabs/hpc-slurm-on-gcp/).

Also, see the Placement Beta Preview User's Guide for information on the Placement Beta Preview offering

## Summary
Placement support changes:
- slurm-cluster.yaml
- slurm.ninja 
- scripts/startup-script.py
## Steps

1. Install GCP Slurm github example and then follow the Slurm README to configure the install 

   ```
   git clone https://github.com/SchedMD/slurm-gcp.git
   ```

2. Create the Placement Group policy using curl

   set POLICYNAME to the name for your policy
   set YOUR_GCP_PROJECT_ID and REGION

   ```
   curl --data "{'name':'POLICYNAME','description':'Group placement for HPC','groupPlacementPolicy':{'collocation': 'COLLOCATED', 'vmCount': 20}}" \
   --header 'Content-Type: application/json'  --header "Authorization: Bearer $(gcloud auth print-access-token)" \
   https://www.googleapis.com/compute/alpha/projects/YOUR_GCP_PROJECT_ID/regions/REGION/resourcePolicies -X POST
   ```

3. Edit the `slurm-cluster.yaml` file
   
   cd to the ./slurm-gcp directory
   edit slurm-cluster.yaml 

   Add the Placement Group policy you created 

   ```
     properties:
        resource_policy        : POLICYNAME
   ```

   Update static_node_count and max_node_count to the maximum cluster size 
   ```
    static_node_count       : 2
    max_node_count          : 20
   ```

   Make sure login_node_count is not commented out 
   ```
    login_node_count        : 1
   ```

   Update zone, region, compute_machine_type. e.g.:
   ```
    zone                    : europe-west4-a
    region                  : europe-west4
    compute_machine_type    : c2-standard-60
   ```

   Set default user and uncomment slurm_version:
   ```
    default_users           : cbrasuell@google.com
    slurm_version           : 19.05-latest
   ```

5. Update  slurm.jinja 

   Make a backup of slurm.ninja
   
   Using your editor, change every 'v1' occurrence to 'alpha' for GCE v2 alpha

   For example:
   ```
   type: compute.alpha.instance
        diskType: https://www.googleapis.com/compute/alpha/projects/{{ env["project"] }}/zones/{{ properties["zone"] }}/diskTypes/{{ properties["controller_disk_type"] }}

   ```

   Find the section {% for n in range(properties['static_node_count']) %}

   Copy and past the resourcePolicies, region, and maintenance parms after properties:

   ```
   properties:
    region: {{ properties["region"] }} 
    scheduling:
      onHostMaintenance: TERMINATE
    resourcePolicies: 
    - https://www.googleapis.com/compute/alpha/projects/{{ env["project"] }}/regions/{{ properties["region"] }}/resourcePolicies/{{ properties["resource_policy"] }}
   ```

    Search for resume.py and insert the following replace statement after "{{ imports["scripts/resume.py"]|indent(12)|" 
    ```
    replace("@RESOURCE_POLICY@",properties["resource_policy"]) | 
    ```

6. Update  ./scripts/resume.py

    Add the RESOURCE_POLICY variable after the python import statements

    ```
    RESOURCE_POLICY ='@RESOURCE_POLICY@'
    ```

    Search for the function: def create_instance 

    Add region, scheduling, and resource policies inside the config data structure    

    ```
    config = {
        'region': REGION,
        'scheduling': {'onHostMaintenance': 'TERMINATE'},
        'resourcePolicies': ['https://www.googleapis.com/compute/alpha/projects/'+PROJECT+'/regions/'+ REGION+'/resourcePolicies/'+RESOURCE_POLICY],
    ```

7. Update  ./scripts/startup-script.py

   find the install_slurm_conf() function and add the following condition to def_mem_per_cpu variable computation

   ```
    def install_slurm_conf():

        machine = expand_machine_type()
        if (MACHINE_TYPE.find('c2')) == 0:
            def_mem_per_cpu = (machine['memory'] / (machine['threads']*machine['cores']*machine['sockets']))
        else:
            def_mem_per_cpu = max(100,
                (machine['memory'] /
                 (machine['threads']*machine['cores']*machine['sockets'])))
   ```

8. Spin up the slurm cluster using the deployment-manager CLI. See also the slurm README

   Note the beta version of deployment-manager

   ```
   gcloud beta deployment-manager deployments [--project=<project id>] create slurm --config slurm-cluster.yaml
   ```

9. Validate the Resource Policy is attached to the VM

    For example, a placement policy named ixpolicy1 deployed into europe-west4 

    ```
    gcloud alpha compute instances describe g1-compute1 --zone europe-west4-a | grep resource
    ```

    Should return:

    ```
    resourcePolicies:
    - https://www.googleapis.com/compute/alpha/projects/slb-wg-prod-rne/regions/europe-west4/resourcePolicies/ixpolicy1
    ```

10. Check the cluster status.

   Wait while the slurm login node configuration completes and the compute nodes register 

   You can see that status of the deployment by viewing:
   https://console.cloud.google.com/deployments

   and viewing the new instances:
   https://console.cloud.google.com/compute/instances

   To verify the deployment, ssh to the login node and run `sinfo` to see how
   many nodes have registered and are in an idle state.

   A message will be broadcast to the terminal when the installation is
   complete. If you log in before the installation is complete, you will either
   need to re-log in after the installation is complete or start a new shell
   (e.g. /bin/bash) to get the correct bash profile.

   ```
   $ gcloud compute [--project=<project id>] ssh [--zone=<zone>] g1-login1
   ```

   ```
   [you@g1-login1 ~]$ sinfo
   PARTITION AVAIL  TIMELIMIT  NODES  STATE NODELIST
   debug*       up   infinite      8  idle~ g1-compute[N+1-max_node_count]
   debug*       up   infinite      2   idle g1-compute[1-N] where N= static_node_count
   ```
   
   If the output doesn't ever match, then check the VM console serial logs to look for any errors. 

   Errors would be related to the scripts/startup-script.py modification

   **NOTE:** By default, Slurm will hide nodes that are in a power_save state --
   "cloud" nodes. The GCP Slurm scripts configure **PrivateData=cloud** in the
   slurm.conf so that the "cloud" nodes are always shown. This is done so that
   nodes that get marked down can be easily seen.

11. Submit jobs on the cluster.

   ```
   [you@g1-login1 ~]$ sbatch -N2 --wrap="srun hostname"
   Submitted batch job 2

   [you@g1-login1 ~]$ cat slurm-2.out
   g1-compute1
   g1-compute2
   ```
   If the slurm output file is not created, then the config may not have completed
   Or, exit the login VM and re-ssh into it.

12. Test running dynamic hosts (NOT TESTED)
    ssh into the g1-controller VM

    cd over to the scripts directory and run the resume.py script

    ```
    sudo -s
    sudo su - slurm
    [slurm@g1-controller ~]$ cd /apps/slurm/scripts/
    [slurm@g1-controller scripts]$ ./resume.py g1-compute-image

    ```
    # Wait until the instance is fully installed. You can verify this by ssh'ing to
    # the instance and verify that there are no messages about installing in the
    # motd.

    TODO/WIP
    ```
    [slurm@g1-controller scripts]$ gcloud compute images create <cluster_name>-compute-image-$(date '+%Y-%m-%d-%H-%M-%S') \
                                                            --source-disk proj2-compute-image \
                                                            --source-disk-zone <zone> --force \
                                                            --family <cluster_name>-compute-image-family \
                                                            --project <project2>
    ```
                                                            
13. Tearing down the deployment.

   **NOTE:** If additional resources (instances, networks) are created (e.g. static compute nodes) other
   than the ones created from the default deployment then they will need to be
   destroyed before deployment can be removed.

   ```
   $ gcloud deployment-manager [--project=<project id>] deployments delete slurm

   ```
   If you any slurm related deployment deletion errors, use the GCP console to delete any VM intances, slurm network, and the slurm Deployment Manager deployment instance

** email from Wyatt
Hey Salvador, sorry for the late reply, wanted to just make your life simpler right away :) Here's a set of slurm scripts that support placement groups for any job under 22 nodes that you can deploy, or you can pull the relevant bits from resume.py, suspend.py, setup.sh, and epilog and prolog scripts. Basically we added Job ID handling to resume.py and suspend.py, and for each job there's a prolog script to call the resume.py script with the job ID so we can create a placement group per job, create the nodes in that group, run the job, and tear the nodes and placement group down unless another job of the same size comes in.

Here's the deployment manager scripts. The Terraform in the newest version doesn't support placement groups yet, but in the near future our development will move over to Terraform, and the actual support for placement groups will be in the next release, which will be Terraform-based.

https://storage.googleapis.com/slurm-gcp/slurm-placement-groups.tgz

Let me know if you have any questions as you start testing with this. You don't need to specify a placement group name, it's generated based on cluster name and job ID per job. Your resource policy quota should be 5 or 10 by default as well. Quota for C2s is limited, though, so keep that in mind as you start running your jobs.
